  "text": "Indeed, in rats anesthetized with isoflurane, histamine injected into the nucleus basalis of Meynert decreased anesthetic-induced burst suppression. This effect was blocked by an H1 but not an H2, antagonist [CITATION_1] . Similar results were obtained with norepinephrine. In rats under desflurane anesthesia, norepinephrine injection into the nucleus basalis of Meynert promoted transient behavioral arousal. Electrophysiologically, norepinephrine injection caused decreased delta power and increased cortical entropy, indicating increased cortical activation. In fact, the level of decreased delta activity in the frontal cortex predicted the level of behavioral arousal, which suggests that these phenomena were linked [CITATION_2] . These studies show that injection of wake-promoting neurotransmitters in the basal forebrain can partially counteract the hypnotic actions of anesthetics.",
